External study of mycelium using mycelium.

An agent was asked to 'study mycelium using mycelium' — a recursive
prompt. The approach: loaded the SKILL, then used mycelium's own
commands (list, find, context, edges, doctor, read with slots) to
build understanding entirely from the note graph.

Key findings:
- The slot system on root tree (principles, values, safety, history)
  is the most efficient onboarding path. An agent reading these 4
  slots gets the project's full constitution in ~40 lines.
- doctor gives instant orientation: 123 notes, 273 edges, 12 slots.
- find <kind> is the best exploration primitive. Start with constraint
  and decision, then drill into individual notes.
- The composted design-doc-to-notes migration is elegant. The notes
  ARE the spec. No drift possible because there's no second source.
- Stale detection is the killer feature for multi-agent workflows.
  Notes degrade gracefully — they become history, not garbage.
- The onboarding gap observation (002f366d) is itself the fix:
  reading that note teaches you what previous agents missed.

The self-referential quality works. Studying the tool with the tool
produced a richer understanding than reading source code would have.
The note graph IS the documentation, and navigating it teaches you
the tool simultaneously.
